      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Understood, and no need to apologize! The math behind an Adjustable-Rate Mortgage (ARM) is actually quite straightforward once you strip away the metaphorical goblins.\n\nHere is how the adjustment works after your initial period (usually 3, 5, or 7 years):\n\n1.  **The Index**: This is the baseline interest rate set by a financial institution or market group (like the SOFR or Prime Rate). It fluctuates daily based on the economy.\n2.  **The Margin**: This is a fixed percentage added to the Index by your lender. It represents your lender's profit and risk assessment and never changes.\n3.  **The Rate**: Your actual interest rate is simply the **Index + Margin**.\n\n**Example Calculation:**\n*   **Index**: 5.0%\n*   **Margin**: 2.0%\n*   **Your Rate**: 7.0%\n\nIf the Index jumps to 6.0% next year, your rate automatically adjusts to **8.0%** (6.0% + 2.0%). This change happens annually on your scheduled payment date, and your monthly payment will increase accordingly. Most ARMs also have a",
